<subSubSection id="C35E4AE42B69FFD5FF7FFE3DD99DFD84" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BFB196F2B69FFD5FF7FFE3DD99DFD84" blockId="1.[151,1437,288,639]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FF7FFE3DDB01FE5C" bold="true" box="[199,322,396,422]" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FEF1FE3DD87DFE5C" authorityName="Ng &amp; Kottelat" authorityYear="2022" box="[329,574,396,422]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="exortivus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FEF1FE3DD87DFE5C" box="[329,574,396,422]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">Silurichthys exortivus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all congeners in having 4 (vs. 6–7) principal rays on the upper caudal-fin lobe, lacking (vs. having) a dorsal fin, and, except for 
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FC43FE00DED7FE30" authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1989" box="[1019,1172,433,459]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sanguineus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FC43FE00DED7FE30" box="[1019,1172,433,459]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">S. sanguineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in lacking (vs. having) pelvic fins. It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FDADFE64D8DBFE14" authorityName="Ng &amp; Tan" authorityYear="2011" box="[533,664,468,495]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ligneolus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FDADFE64D8DBFE14" box="[533,664,468,495]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">S. ligneolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FD77FE64D92AFE14" authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1989" box="[719,873,469,495]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sanguineus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FD77FE64D92AFE14" box="[719,873,469,495]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">S. sanguineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a caudal fin with distinct, asymmetrical lobes (vs. obliquely truncate and without distinct lobes), and in the number of anal-fin rays (54 vs. 
<quantity id="4CBCB48A2B69FFD5FB57FE49DF11FDE8" box="[1263,1362,504,531]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1303" metricValueMax="1.143" metricValueMin="1.1176" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" unit="in" value="44.5" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="44.0">44–45 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FAE1FE48DAA3FDCC" authorityName="Ng &amp; Tan" authorityYear="2011" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ligneolus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FAE1FE48DAA3FDCC" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">S. ligneolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<quantity id="4CBCB48A2B69FFD5FEAFFDADDB0CFDCC" box="[279,335,540,566]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" unit="in" value="60.0">60 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="4C4462EC2B69FFD5FEEEFDACDBB3FDCC" authorityName="Roberts" authorityYear="1989" box="[342,496,541,567]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Siluridae" genus="Silurichthys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="186" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sanguineus">
<emphasis id="B930C57D2B69FFD5FEEEFDACDBB3FDCC" box="[342,496,541,567]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="186">S. sanguineus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The following combination of characters additionally distinguishes it from congeners: body depth at anus 14.0% SL, caudal peduncle depth 5.1% SL, upper lobe of caudal fin 1.1 times longer than lower lobe, 1 raker on first gill arch, 48 vertebrae and brown mottled body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
